M|test-driven-development|name: test-driven-dev
M|test-driven-development|description: Use when implementing any feature or bugfix, before writing implementation code
M|test-driven-development|version: 1.0.0
M|test-driven-development|platforms: []
M|test-driven-development|metadata:
M|test-driven-development|hermes:
M|test-driven-development|tags: [dev, nextjs, typescript, architecture, vercel, api-routes, build, productivity]
M|test-driven-development|Write the test first. Watch it fail. Write minimal code to pass.
M|test-driven-development|**Core principle:** If you didn't watch the test fail, you don't know if it tests the right thing.
M|test-driven-development|**Violating the letter of the rules is violating the spirit of the rules.**
M|test-driven-development|**Always:**
M|test-driven-development|- New features
M|test-driven-development|- Bug fixes
M|test-driven-development|- Refactoring
M|test-driven-development|- Behavior changes
M|test-driven-development|**Exceptions (ask your human partner):**
M|test-driven-development|- Throwaway prototypes
M|test-driven-development|- Generated code
M|test-driven-development|- cfg files
M|test-driven-development|Thinking "skip TDD just this once"? Stop. That's rationalization.
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|NO prd CODE WITHOUT A FAILING TEST FIRST
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Write code before the test? Delete it. Start over.
M|test-driven-development|**No exceptions:**
M|test-driven-development|- Don't keep it as "reference"
M|test-driven-development|- Don't "adapt" it while writing tests
M|test-driven-development|- Don't look at it
M|test-driven-development|- Delete means delete
M|test-driven-development|Implement fresh from tests. Period.
M|test-driven-development|```dot
M|test-driven-development|digraph tdd_cycle {
M|test-driven-development|rankdir=LR;
M|test-driven-development|red [label="RED\nWrite failing test", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ffcccc"];
M|test-driven-development|verify_red [label="Verify fails\ncorrectly", shape=diamond];
M|test-driven-development|green [label="GREEN\nMinimal code", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ccffcc"];
M|test-driven-development|verify_green [label="Verify passes\nAll green", shape=diamond];
M|test-driven-development|refactor [label="REFACTOR\nClean up", shape=box, style=filled, fillcolor="#ccccff"];
M|test-driven-development|next [label="Next", shape=ellipse];
M|test-driven-development|red -> verify_red;
M|test-driven-development|verify_red -> green [label="yes"];
M|test-driven-development|verify_red -> red [label="wrong\nfailure"];
M|test-driven-development|green -> verify_green;
M|test-driven-development|verify_green -> refactor [label="yes"];
M|test-driven-development|verify_green -> green [label="no"];
M|test-driven-development|refactor -> verify_green [label="stay\ngreen"];
M|test-driven-development|verify_green -> next;
M|test-driven-development|next -> red;
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Write one minimal test showing what should happen.
M|test-driven-development|<Good>
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|test('retries failed operations 3 times', async () => {
M|test-driven-development|let attempts = 0;
M|test-driven-development|const operation = () => {
M|test-driven-development|attempts++;
M|test-driven-development|if (attempts < 3) throw new Error('fail');
M|test-driven-development|return 'success';
M|test-driven-development|};
M|test-driven-development|const result = await retryOperation(operation);
M|test-driven-development|expect(result).toBe('success');
M|test-driven-development|expect(attempts).toBe(3);
M|test-driven-development|});
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Clear name, tests real behavior, one thing
M|test-driven-development|</Good>
M|test-driven-development|<Bad>
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|test('retry works', async () => {
M|test-driven-development|const mock = jest.fn()
M|test-driven-development|.mockRejectedValueOnce(new Error())
M|test-driven-development|.mockRejectedValueOnce(new Error())
M|test-driven-development|.mockResolvedValueOnce('success');
M|test-driven-development|await retryOperation(mock);
M|test-driven-development|expect(mock).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(3);
M|test-driven-development|});
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Vague name, tests mock not code
M|test-driven-development|</Bad>
M|test-driven-development|**Requirements:**
M|test-driven-development|- One behavior
M|test-driven-development|- Clear name
M|test-driven-development|- Real code (no mocks unless unavoidable)
M|test-driven-development|**MANDATORY. Never skip.**
M|test-driven-development|```bash
M|test-driven-development|npm test path/to/test.test.ts
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Confirm:
M|test-driven-development|- Test fails (not errors)
M|test-driven-development|- Failure message is expected
M|test-driven-development|- Fails because feature missing (not typos)
M|test-driven-development|**Test passes?** You're testing existing behavior. Fix test.
M|test-driven-development|**Test errors?** Fix error, re-run until it fails correctly.
M|test-driven-development|Write simplest code to pass the test.
M|test-driven-development|<Good>
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|async function retryOperation<T>(fn: () => Promise<T>): Promise<T> {
M|test-driven-development|for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
M|test-driven-development|try {
M|test-driven-development|return await fn();
M|test-driven-development|} catch (e) {
M|test-driven-development|if (i === 2) throw e;
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|throw new Error('unreachable');
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Just enough to pass
M|test-driven-development|</Good>
M|test-driven-development|<Bad>
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|async function retryOperation<T>(
M|test-driven-development|fn: () => Promise<T>,
M|test-driven-development|options?: {
M|test-driven-development|maxRetries?: number;
M|test-driven-development|backoff?: 'linear' | 'exponential';
M|test-driven-development|onRetry?: (attempt: number) => void;
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|): Promise<T> {
M|test-driven-development|// YAGNI
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Over-engineered
M|test-driven-development|</Bad>
M|test-driven-development|Don't add features, refactor other code, or "improve" beyond the test.
M|test-driven-development|**MANDATORY.**
M|test-driven-development|```bash
M|test-driven-development|npm test path/to/test.test.ts
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|Confirm:
M|test-driven-development|- Test passes
M|test-driven-development|- Other tests still pass
M|test-driven-development|- Output pristine (no errors, warnings)
M|test-driven-development|**Test fails?** Fix code, not test.
M|test-driven-development|**Other tests fail?** Fix now.
M|test-driven-development|After green only:
M|test-driven-development|- Remove duplication
M|test-driven-development|- Improve names
M|test-driven-development|- Extract helpers
M|test-driven-development|Keep tests green. Don't add behavior.
M|test-driven-development|Next failing test for next feature.
M|test-driven-development|| Quality | Good | Bad |
M|test-driven-development||---------|------|-----|
M|test-driven-development|| **Minimal** | One thing. "and" in name? Split it. | `test('validates email and domain and whitespace')` |
M|test-driven-development|| **Clear** | Name describes behavior | `test('test1')` |
M|test-driven-development|| **Shows intent** | Demonstrates desired API | Obscures what code should do |
M|test-driven-development|**"I'll write tests after to verify it works"**
M|test-driven-development|Tests written after code pass immediately. Passing immediately proves nothing:
M|test-driven-development|- Might test wrong thing
M|test-driven-development|- Might test implementation, not behavior
M|test-driven-development|- Might miss edge cases you forgot
M|test-driven-development|- You never saw it catch the bug
M|test-driven-development|Test-first forces you to see the test fail, proving it actually tests something.
M|test-driven-development|**"I already manually tested all the edge cases"**
M|test-driven-development|Manual testing is ad-hoc. You think you tested everything but:
M|test-driven-development|- No record of what you tested
M|test-driven-development|- Can't re-run when code changes
M|test-driven-development|- Easy to forget cases under pressure
M|test-driven-development|- "It worked when I tried it" ≠ comprehensive
M|test-driven-development|Automated tests are systematic. They run the same way every time.
M|test-driven-development|**"Deleting X hours of work is wasteful"**
M|test-driven-development|Sunk cost fallacy. The time is already gone. Your choice now:
M|test-driven-development|- Delete and rewrite with TDD (X more hours, high confidence)
M|test-driven-development|- Keep it and add tests after (30 min, low confidence, likely bugs)
M|test-driven-development|The "waste" is keeping code you can't trust. Working code without real tests is tec debt.
M|test-driven-development|**"TDD is dogmatic, being pragmatic means adapting"**
M|test-driven-development|TDD IS pragmatic:
M|test-driven-development|- Finds bugs before commit (faster than debugging after)
M|test-driven-development|- Prevents regressions (tests catch breaks immediately)
M|test-driven-development|- Documents behavior (tests show how to use code)
M|test-driven-development|- Enables refactoring (change freely, tests catch breaks)
M|test-driven-development|"Pragmatic" shortcuts = debugging in prd = slower.
M|test-driven-development|**"Tests after achieve the same goals - it's spirit not ritual"**
M|test-driven-development|No. Tests-after answer "What does this do?" Tests-first answer "What should this do?"
M|test-driven-development|Tests-after are biased by your implementation. You test what you built, not what's required. You verify remembered edge cases, not discovered ones.
M|test-driven-development|Tests-first force edge case discovery before implementing. Tests-after verify you remembered everything (you didn't).
M|test-driven-development|30 minutes of tests after ≠ TDD. You get coverage, lose proof tests work.
M|test-driven-development|| Excuse | Reality |
M|test-driven-development||--------|---------|
M|test-driven-development|| "Too simple to test" | Simple code breaks. Test takes 30 seconds. |
M|test-driven-development|| "I'll test after" | Tests passing immediately prove nothing. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Tests after achieve same goals" | Tests-after = "what does this do?" Tests-first = "what should this do?" |
M|test-driven-development|| "Already manually tested" | Ad-hoc ≠ systematic. No record, can't re-run. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Deleting X hours is wasteful" | Sunk cost fallacy. Keeping unverified code is tec debt. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Keep as reference, write tests first" | You'll adapt it. That's testing after. Delete means delete. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Need to explore first" | Fine. Throw away exploration, start with TDD. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Test hard = design unclear" | Listen to test. Hard to test = hard to use. |
M|test-driven-development|| "TDD will slow me down" | TDD faster than debugging. Pragmatic = test-first. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Manual test faster" | Manual doesn't prove edge cases. You'll re-test every change. |
M|test-driven-development|| "Existing code has no tests" | You're improving it. Add tests for existing code. |
M|test-driven-development|- Code before test
M|test-driven-development|- Test after implementation
M|test-driven-development|- Test passes immediately
M|test-driven-development|- Can't explain why test failed
M|test-driven-development|- Tests added "later"
M|test-driven-development|- Rationalizing "just this once"
M|test-driven-development|- "I already manually tested it"
M|test-driven-development|- "Tests after achieve the same purpose"
M|test-driven-development|- "It's about spirit not ritual"
M|test-driven-development|- "Keep as reference" or "adapt existing code"
M|test-driven-development|- "Already spent X hours, deleting is wasteful"
M|test-driven-development|- "TDD is dogmatic, I'm being pragmatic"
M|test-driven-development|- "This is different because..."
M|test-driven-development|**All of these mean: Delete code. Start over with TDD.**
M|test-driven-development|**Bug:** Empty email accepted
M|test-driven-development|**RED**
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|test('rejects empty email', async () => {
M|test-driven-development|const result = await submitForm({ email: '' });
M|test-driven-development|expect(result.error).toBe('Email required');
M|test-driven-development|});
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|**Verify RED**
M|test-driven-development|```bash
M|test-driven-development|$ npm test
M|test-driven-development|FAIL: expected 'Email required', got undefined
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|**GREEN**
M|test-driven-development|```typescript
M|test-driven-development|function submitForm(data: FormData) {
M|test-driven-development|if (!data.email?.trim()) {
M|test-driven-development|return { error: 'Email required' };
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|// ...
M|test-driven-development|}
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|**Verify GREEN**
M|test-driven-development|```bash
M|test-driven-development|$ npm test
M|test-driven-development|PASS
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|**REFACTOR**
M|test-driven-development|Extract validation for multiple fields if needed.
M|test-driven-development|Before marking work complete:
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Every new function/method has a test
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Watched each test fail before implementing
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Each test failed for expected reason (feature missing, not typo)
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Wrote minimal code to pass each test
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] All tests pass
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Output pristine (no errors, warnings)
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Tests use real code (mocks only if unavoidable)
M|test-driven-development|- [ ] Edge cases and errors covered
M|test-driven-development|Can't check all boxes? You skipped TDD. Start over.
M|test-driven-development|| Problem | Solution |
M|test-driven-development||---------|----------|
M|test-driven-development|| Don't know how to test | Write wished-for API. Write assertion first. Ask your human partner. |
M|test-driven-development|| Test too complicated | Design too complicated. Simplify interface. |
M|test-driven-development|| Must mock everything | Code too coupled. Use dependency injection. |
M|test-driven-development|| Test setup huge | Extract helpers. Still complex? Simplify design. |
M|test-driven-development|Bug found? Write failing test reproducing it. Follow TDD cycle. Test proves fix and prevents regression.
M|test-driven-development|Never fix bugs without a test.
M|test-driven-development|When adding mocks or test utilities, read @testing-anti-patterns.md to avoid common pitfalls:
M|test-driven-development|- Testing mock behavior instead of real behavior
M|test-driven-development|- Adding test-only methods to prd classes
M|test-driven-development|- Mocking without understanding dependencies
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|prd code → test exists and failed first
M|test-driven-development|Otherwise → not TDD
M|test-driven-development|```
M|test-driven-development|No exceptions without your human partner's permission.